english:
  title: A Letter to Master Gyeongsa
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I bow my head respectfully before you, Master.

    How fares your practice of the Way these days? May ten thousand blessings attend your cultivation. My longing for your presence knows no respite, even in these brief intervals.

    Unworthy though I am, I have received your kindness and live without ailment, passing my days in leisure and wandering. When I visited you yesterday and heard your lofty discourse—eloquent and unceasing—it moved me to listen anew. Such wisdom cannot be fathomed by those of ordinary and vulgar mind. I, having a nature inclined toward arrogance, have never bowed to another. Yet upon hearing your words, Master, I found myself instantly humbled by your magnanimity. It is as they say: just as the crystalline discourse of Wei Jie made Pingzi fall over in rapture.

    In ancient times, Xie An dwelt in Kuaiji and, with the Buddhist master Zhi Dun, abandoned himself to mountains and valleys, harboring no worldly ambitions. I too have always harbored a spirit unbound by convention and yearned for the path beyond. How much more so, having weathered many sorrows, I have long lamented that my resolve was never made early enough.

    Now, fortunate that we dwell near one another, I lack the strength to renounce worldly affairs and follow the staff of the wandering sage to fulfill my deepest aspirations. I remain but a laughingstock to those dwelling between stream and forest. What cause for sorrow!

    Yet as spring arrives and my duties lighten, I shall visit you ere long. When we meet face to face, all that stirs within my heart shall be laid bare. Until then, I ask only that you nurture your spirit, tend your nature, conduct yourself with timely self-restraint, and receive the warmth of these heartfelt wishes.
  footnotes:
    - Wei Jie (衛玠) was a renowned intellectual of Eastern Jin known for his refined discourse; Pingzi (平子) refers to Zhang Heng, the brilliant polymath. The allusion suggests being so moved by eloquent wisdom that one loses composure.
    - Xie An (謝安) and the Buddhist monk Zhi Dun (支遁) were historical figures celebrated for their philosophical friendship and retreat into natural solitude during the Jin dynasty.
    - The "staff" (錫杖) is a traditional implement carried by wandering Buddhist monks, symbolizing the monastic life and spiritual pursuit.
